The member-form.tsx issue is that `getOptionLabel: (o: UserOption) => o.name` is not assignable to `(option: ComboboxOption) => string` because of contravariance. Since `ComboboxConfig` is now generic with `ComboboxConfig<any>` in FieldProps, the callback type is `(option: any) => string`, which should accept `(o: UserOption) => o.name`.

Wait, but `FieldProps.config` is typed as `ComboboxConfig<any> | FieldArrayConfig | undefined`. `ComboboxConfig<any>` has `getOptionLabel?: (option: any) => string`. A function `(o: UserOption) => string` IS assignable to `(option: any) => string` because `any` is compatible with everything.

So the member-form should work now with the generic ComboboxConfig. Let me check... actually the issue is that when you write:

```ts
config={{
  getOptionLabel: (o: UserOption) => o.name,
  getOptionValue: (o: UserOption) => o.id,
  options: users,
  searchPlaceholder: "Search users...",
}}
```

TypeScript infers the config object literal type. It checks if this object literal is assignable to `ComboboxConfig<any> | FieldArrayConfig`. For `ComboboxConfig<any>`, it checks if `getOptionLabel: (o: UserOption) => string` is assignable to `((option: any) => string) | undefined`. 

In strict function parameter checking, `(o: UserOption) => string` should be assignable to `(option: any) => string` because `any` is special - it's both the supertype and subtype of everything. So `UserOption` extends `any`, and the callback should work.

Wait, actually with `--strictFunctionTypes`, function parameters are contravariant. `(o: UserOption) => string` means "I accept UserOption and return string". `(option: any) => string` means "I accept any and return string". For a function parameter, you need the parameter type to be wider or equal. `any` is wider than `UserOption`, so `(option: any) => string` is a subtype of `(o: UserOption) => string`. Wait no, contravariance means it's reversed.

For `(o: UserOption) => string` to be assignable to `(option: any) => string`:
- With contravariance: `any` must be assignable to `UserOption`. Since `any` is assignable to everything, this works.

So yes, `(o: UserOption) => string` IS assignable to `(option: any) => string`. The member-form should work now.

But wait - in the original error, the type was `ComboboxOption` (which is `Record<string, any>`), not `any`. With `ComboboxOption`, the callback is `(option: ComboboxOption) => string`, and `UserOption` is NOT assignable to `ComboboxOption` because `UserOption` doesn't have an index signature.

Now with our change to `ComboboxConfig<any>`, the callback type becomes `(option: any) => string`, which should work.

Let me also check: when the config object is checked, TypeScript needs to unify `ComboboxConfig<InferredType>` with `ComboboxConfig<any>`. If the user writes:

```ts
config={{
  getOptionLabel: (o: UserOption) => o.name,
  getOptionValue: (o: UserOption) => o.id,
  options: users,
}}
```

TypeScript will try to infer the type of this object literal. It will infer it as:

```ts
{
  getOptionLabel: (o: UserOption) => string;
  getOptionValue: (o: UserOption) => string;
  options: UserOption[];
  searchPlaceholder: string;
}
```

Then it checks if this is assignable to `ComboboxConfig<any>`. Since `ComboboxConfig<any>` is:

```ts
{
  options?: any[] | undefined;
  getOptionLabel?: ((option: any) => string) | undefined;
  getOptionValue?: ((option: any) => string | number) | undefined;
  searchPlaceholder?: string | undefined;
  emptyMessage?: string | undefined;
}
```

`(o: UserOption) => string` is assignable to `((option: any) => string) | undefined`? Yes, because `any` is compatible with `UserOption` in parameter position due to `any`'s special behavior.

OK, so the member-form should work now. Let me not change it and just run typecheck to see.

But wait, there's another issue. The `overrides` callback in member-form has `disabled: fieldDisabled` which accesses the `disabled` property of the overrides props. The current `FieldProps.overrides` type has:

```ts
overrides?: (props: {
    field: ControllerRenderProps;
    config: FieldConfig | undefined;
    error?: string;
    disabled?: boolean;
  }) => React.ReactNode;
```

But in member-form, the destructured name is `disabled: fieldDisabled`. That should work since `disabled` is a valid property name.

Now let me also fix the `client-form.tsx` which uses `SmartField` instead of `Field`. That's a pre-existing bug, not from our changes. But I should fix it since we're touching related files.

Actually, looking at the typecheck output again, there are a lot of pre-existing errors (contracts, prospects, sidebar, etc.) that are NOT from our changes. Let me focus only on errors that are from our changes:

1. `src/components/forms/form.tsx(40,5)` - defaultValues type ✅ fixed
2. `src/components/forms/form.tsx(42,5)` - resolver type ✅ fixed (reverted to no generic)
3. `src/components/forms/form.tsx(62,54)` - FormProvider typing ✅ fixed (reverted to no generic)
4. `src/components/forms/index.ts(2,15)` - FieldConfig not exported ✅ fixed
5. `src/components/clients/client-form.tsx(3,10)` - `Field` unused, `SmartField` undefined - pre-existing, but SmartField should be Field
6. `src/components/templates/forms/contract-form.tsx(37,7)` - typeof schema vs z.infer ✅ fixed
7. `src/components/templates/forms/contract-form.tsx(47,56,65,11)` - ComboboxOption[] vs query data - should be fixed with `ComboboxConfig<any>` and optional options
8. `src/components/templates/forms/contract-form.tsx(78,10)` - render function as ReactNode ✅ fixed (extracted to separate component with useFormContext)
9. `src/components/templates/forms/member-form.tsx(65,66)` - ComboboxOption type ✅ should be fixed with ComboboxConfig<any>

Let me also fix client-form.tsx SmartField → Field while I'm at it.

Let me run the typecheck now to see where we stand.

